--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PART V: ISLAMIC ETHICS STATEMENT
(Companion Document — Accessible Explanation of the Restrictions Above)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This section is not a legal instrument. It is an explanation, written plainly,
of why this license exists and what Islamic principles underlie its
restrictions. It is addressed to every person who encounters this Software —
Muslim and non-Muslim alike.

WHY THIS LICENSE EXISTS

We are Muslims. We believe that human beings are trustees (khulafa) on this
earth, as Allah says in Surah Al-Baqarah (2:30), and that this trusteeship
carries responsibility. Every act a person performs — including writing and
distributing software — is an act that will be weighed. We did not want to
release our work into the world with no consideration of how it might be used
to harm the people Allah created.

We are not under any illusion that a license can enforce morality. It cannot.
People who intend to do harm will not be stopped by a text file. But we
believe in the Islamic principle of bara'a, the disavowal of wrongdoing. By
stating clearly what this Software must not be used for, we have discharged
our duty to speak clearly. What a person does after hearing the truth is
between them and Allah.

THE FIVE OBJECTIVES OF ISLAMIC LAW (AL-MAQASID AL-KHAMSAH)

Classical Islamic scholars identified five essential things that Islamic law
exists to protect. These are:

  1. The preservation of religion (hifz al-din)
  2. The preservation of life (hifz al-nafs)
  3. The preservation of intellect and reason (hifz al-'aql)
  4. The preservation of lineage and family (hifz al-nasl)
  5. The preservation of wealth and property (hifz al-mal)

Every restriction in Part II of this license maps to one or more of these
objectives. Riba destroys wealth and exploits the vulnerable. Pornography
corrupts lineage and chastity. Gambling corrupts wealth and reason.
Intoxicants destroy the intellect. Surveillance and oppression destroy life
and religious freedom. Weapons of mass destruction destroy life entirely.
Fraud destroys wealth and trust.

We are not innovating new ethics. We are applying a 1,400-year-old ethical
framework, refined by generations of scholars, to a new domain.

ON THE PROHIBITIONS SPECIFICALLY

Riba (Usury): Allah declared war, in the Quran itself, on those who persist
in riba after being warned (Al-Baqarah 2:279). This is language used for
almost nothing else in the Quran. The scholars are unanimous in its
prohibition. We have narrowed our restriction to predatory lending targeting
vulnerable individuals because we sought to be honest and specific rather
than broad and unenforceable. We acknowledge that a fuller Islamic vision of
finance would go further; this restriction represents the minimum that
conscience demands.

Pornography: The Prophet, peace be upon him, described the eye, the heart,
and the hand as all capable of their own form of zina (Sahih Bukhari, 6243).
A platform dedicated to the mass industrial production of sexually explicit
content is, in our view, one of the most significant engines of moral
corruption in contemporary society. We will not knowingly contribute to it.

Gambling: The Quran explicitly names maysir (gambling) alongside intoxicants
as "defilement from the work of Satan" (Al-Ma'idah 5:90). This is not an
obscure ruling. It is among the clearest prohibitions in the primary sources.

Intoxicants: The hadith is definitive: "Every intoxicant is khamr, and every
khamr is forbidden" (Sahih Muslim, 2003). The category is broad and the
ruling is absolute. We have been careful to exclude medical and harm-reduction
software, because the preservation of life takes precedence over categorical
application of this restriction.

Surveillance and Oppression: The Quran commands justice ('adl) and forbids
oppression (zulm) in terms that leave no room for qualification. Allah says:
"And Allah does not like the oppressors" (Ali 'Imran 3:140). The Muslim
communities most harmed by mass surveillance technology in the contemporary
world are Muslim minorities under authoritarian regimes. We have a particular
duty not to contribute to systems that hunt our brothers and sisters for the
crime of practicing their faith.

Weapons of Mass Destruction: Islamic rules of warfare (fiqh al-jihad) are
explicit that non-combatants must not be targeted. The Prophet, peace be upon
him, prohibited the killing of women, children, the elderly, and monks
(Abu Dawud, 2614). A weapon designed to kill indiscriminately cannot be
made compliant with these rules. There is no scholarly position in mainstream
Islamic jurisprudence that permits the deliberate mass killing of civilian
populations.

Fraud and Deception: The Prophet, peace be upon him, walked away from a
seller who had concealed defective goods and said: "Whoever deceives us is
not of us" (Sahih Muslim, 101). Systematic, industrialized deception for
material gain is simply incompatible with the Islamic character (akhlaq) that
every Muslim is obligated to embody.

AN INVITATION

We do not release this Software with hostility toward anyone. We release it
with the hope that it will be genuinely useful, that its restrictions will
cause those who encounter them to reflect — even briefly — on what they are
building and why, and that the explanation above might, for some reader,
be an opening toward understanding the ethical coherence of Islamic values.

The Prophet Muhammad, peace be upon him, said: "None of you truly believes
until he loves for his brother what he loves for himself" (Sahih Bukhari,
13). We want, for every human being, what we want for ourselves: a life of
dignity, honesty, and safety from exploitation. This license is a small
expression of that wish.

    "Our Lord, accept this from us. Indeed, You are the Hearing, the Knowing."
    — Surah Al-Baqarah (2:127)

